9. However, at the hearing it emerged that De Beers\'92 pre-merger control over the Venetia mine is not as pervasive as suggested in their submission to the Commission. In terms of its agreement with Saturn, De Beers is obliged to maintain production above certain levels. This obligation continues for so long as Saturn remains in existence. De Beers has also made an offer to buy out ICH. At the time of this decision ICH had not yet decided on the offer but, if it accepts, then De Beers would have acquired a 100 percent interest in Saturn, which would accordingly dissolve, and De Beers would no longer be bound by the production constraint. This means that De Beers could unilaterally make a decision to reduce production at the largest diamond mine in South Africa.}
